This looks like an internal problem with OpenVINO and the OpenVINO EP and it'll be specific to your environment and how the ORT native library searches its library path. I don't think it's a problem on the Java side and hopefully some of the ORT people who work on the OpenVINO EP can help.

The test passed presumably because the CMake script ORT uses to build set the library path appropriately. You could explicitly put the OpenVINO libraries in your ldconfig which should mean ORT can find them when run via Java, but I don't have access to an OpenVINO environment to help you debug it. One thing you can do to check is to find `libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so` on your filesystem and then run `ldd` within the terminal that you use to run the Java program. That should have the same library loading environment, and if ldd says it can't find the OpenVINO libraries then you have an environment configuration problem which is outside of the control of ORT. If ldd can find it then the ORT native loader isn't probing the environment properly, and I don't know much about the dynamic library loading that ORT does, that's not my area of expertise.

I don't think so, but the full set of OpenVINO settings aren't available in Java yet so if you've set those in python we might need to add support for that.

Java needs more careful attention to how data flows into and out of the system and you need to avoid using Java arrays for multidimensional objects as they are very slow.

I feel the inference time of onnxruntime with CPU was better than OpenVINO in both python and java. 

## with onnxruntime-openvino (python)
### setup:
python version: 3.9.6
onnxruntime-openvino-wheel-from: zip file from [intel/onnxruntime](https://github.com/intel/onnxruntime/releases), below code tested with [whl zip](https://github.com/intel/onnxruntime/releases/download/v3.0/ubuntu18-v3.0-python3.9-whl.zip)

### code:
```
import time
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime
# ..........
# ..............
# openvino also do a Graph optimization, so disable onnxruntime optimization
options.graph_optimization_level = onnxruntime.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL

session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(model_path, options)

# if we didn't add this line, that also works. The inference time will be the same.
# [referred]:
# https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/reference/execution-providers/OpenVINO-ExecutionProvider.html#configuration-options
session.set_providers(['OpenVINOExecutionProvider'], [{"device_type": "CPU_FP32"}])

preprocess_start = time.time()
img_data = preprocess(img)
preprocess_elapsed = time.time() - preprocess_start

input_name = session.get_inputs()[0].name
infer_start = time.time()
pred = session.run(None, {input_name: img_data})
infer_elapsed = time.time() - infer_start.

# ................
# ................

print(f"pre-process time: {preprocess_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"inference time: {infer_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"post-process time: {post_process_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"number of objects detected: {len(objects)}")

```
```
Output:
pre-process time: 0.077 sec
inference time: 2.254 sec
post-process time: 0.001 sec
number of objects detected: 10

```
#### P.S:
    The CPU version of onnxruntime took inference time: 1.9sec. In **java** also the same thing happens.

## with openvino (python)
### setup:
python version: 3.9.6
openvino-wheel-from: [PYPI](https://pypi.org/project/openvino/)
### code
```
from openvino.inference_engine import IECore, IENetwork

from openvino.inference_engine.ie_api import ExecutableNetwork, InputInfoPtr

.....
.....
ie: IECore = IECore()
net: IENetwork = ie.read_network(model=xml_path, weights=bin_path)

input_info: InputInfoPtr = net.input_info['image']

input_info_layer: str
input_layer: str
input_info_layer, input_layer = net.input_info

preprocess_start = time.time()
img_data = preprocess(img)
preprocess_elapsed = time.time() - preprocess_start

# reshape the input_layer for dynamic input
# [refer]:
# https://docs.openvinotoolkit.org/latest/ie_python_api/classie__api_1_1IENetwork.html#a6683f0291db25f908f8d6720ab2f221a
net.reshape({input_layer: img_data.shape})

input_dim: Tuple[int, int] = (1500, 2100)[::-1]
image_info: List[int] = input_info.input_data.shape

max_requests: int = 12
exec_net: ExecutableNetwork = ie.load_network(network=net, device_name="CPU", num_requests=max_requests)

inputs: Dict = {input_info_layer: image_info, input_layer: img_data}

infer_start = time.time()
outputs = exec_net.infer(inputs)
infer_elapsed = time.time() - infer_start

# ....................
# .................

print(f"pre-process time: {preprocess_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"inference time: {infer_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"post-process time: {post_process_elapsed:.3f} sec")
print(f"number of objects detected: {len(objects)}")

```
```
Output:
pre-process time: 0.082 sec
inference time: 0.923 sec
post-process time: 0.001 sec
number of objects detected: 10
```
